================================================================================
13. LICENSE COMPATIBILITY AND DEPENDENCIES
================================================================================

13.1 CORE PRINCIPLE: FILE-LEVEL LICENSING
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
AOL applies ONLY to AOL-Licensed Files.

The license does NOT extend to:
- Dependencies (external packages/libraries)
- System libraries
- Build tools
- Configuration files
- Files explicitly licensed under other licenses

13.2 DEPENDENCIES AND EXTERNAL CODE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
When AOL-Licensed Files use dependencies (npm packages, system libraries, GPL
libraries, etc.):

EFFECT ON AOL FILES:
- AOL-Licensed Files remain under AOL
- Dependencies do NOT "infect" or override AOL files
- Each work retains its original license

EFFECT ON DEPENDENCIES:
- Dependencies retain their original licenses
- You must comply with dependency license terms
- Dependency licenses do NOT control AOL files

LEGAL BASIS:
- Copyright applies only to copyrighted work
- Dependencies are separate works with separate copyrights
- No license can override copyright holder consent
- Merely using/linking does not create derivative works

13.3 GPL INCOMPATIBILITY AND RECOMMENDATIONS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
AOL is incompatible with licenses that claim to extend their terms to entire
projects, including:
- GNU General Public License (GPL v2, GPL v3)
- GNU Affero General Public License (AGPL)

POSITION:
Each file retains its original license. AOL-Licensed Files remain under AOL
regardless of what dependencies are used. GPL files remain GPL. Neither
license overrides the other.

AOL copyright holders have not consented to license conversion of AOL files
under any circumstances.

STRONG RECOMMENDATION:
Avoid GPL-licensed dependencies in AOL projects. While each file technically
retains its own license, the conflicting requirements create legal uncertainty
and distribution difficulties.

RECOMMENDED ALTERNATIVES:
Instead of GPL libraries, use:
- MIT License
- BSD Licenses
- Apache License 2.0
- ISC License
- Mozilla Public License 2.0

These licenses are compatible with AOL and avoid legal conflicts.

IF YOU MUST USE GPL CODE:
- Understand that distribution may be legally problematic
- Each file keeps its own license (no conversion)
- You must comply with both licenses for their respective files
- If compliance with both is impossible, distribution is prohibited
- Seek legal counsel before distributing combined works

13.4 COMPATIBLE LICENSES
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
AOL works well with permissive licenses that do not claim project-wide scope:

COMPATIBLE:
- MIT License
- BSD Licenses (2-Clause, 3-Clause)
- Apache License 2.0
- ISC License
- Other permissive licenses

Each component retains its original license when combined.

13.5 PRACTICAL COMPATIBILITY
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
For Public Distribution of combined works:
1. Each component must comply with its own license
2. Provide clear license notices for each component
3. Make source code available as required by each license
4. AOL files keep AOL headers
5. Dependencies keep their own license notices

If license requirements conflict and cannot both be satisfied, seek
alternative dependencies or do not distribute the combined work.

13.6 LEGAL DISCLAIMER
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
This section represents the legal position of AOL copyright holders.

Users combining AOL code with code under other licenses should seek
independent legal counsel to understand their obligations and risks.

Courts have not definitively ruled on license compatibility questions in
most jurisdictions.

